In haplodiploids, female offspring of the same (haploid) father all share his full paternal haplotype. For this reason, the sire variance in the above model equals half of the additive genetic variance. Female offspring of the same (diploid) mother, in contrast, share only 50% of their maternal haplotype because of Mendelian segregation and recombination. Thus, as in diploids, the dam variance in the above model equals one-quarter of the additive genetic variance. Thus, the above sire-dam model is a type of reduced animal model (Quaas and Pollak 1980), but the dam variance equals half the sire variance, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
